oc:kn_14ea5d2c a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing a cold email from scratch" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Check for product-marketing-context.md and read it first. 2. Gather inputs: who (role, company, why them), what outcome, what value, what proof, any research signals. 3. Choose framework that fits (PAS, BAB, QVC, Observation→Problem→Proof→Ask, or freeform). 4. Write subject line: 2–4 words, lowercase, internal-looking. 5. Write body with peer voice, you/your-dominant, one proof point, low-friction CTA. 6. Quality check: sounds human? Would you reply? Every sentence serves reader? Personalization connected to problem? One clear ask?" ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_34cd13b2 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When personalizing cold emails" ;
    oc:directiveContent "If you remove the personalized opening and the email still makes sense, the personalization isn't working. The observation must naturally lead into why you're reaching out. Apply the 'So What?' test — if the prospect's answer is nothing, rewrite." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Personalization drives 50–250% more replies (Lavender), but only when connected to the problem. Disconnected personalization is just an attention hack that recipients detect instantly" .

oc:kn_41fe337a a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing or editing cold email body copy" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Brevity is the top performance lever: 25–75 words optimal, 83% more replies under 75 words. 3rd–5th grade reading level = 67% more replies. Every sentence must earn its place — if it doesn't move the reader toward replying, cut it." ;
    oc:hasRationale "70% of cold emails are written above 10th-grade level. Shorter, simpler emails dramatically outperform across all seniority levels and industries" .

oc:kn_6305c376 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating a follow-up sequence" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Send initial email (Day 0) with maximum personalization. 2. Follow-up 1 (Day 3): different angle, new value piece. 3. Follow-up 2 (Day 7–8): social proof or case study. 4. Follow-up 3 (Day 14): new insight or resource. 5. Follow-up 4 (Day 21–28): breakup email acknowledging silence, leaving door open. Cap at 5 total emails. Each must stand alone and add one new value proposition." ;
    oc:stepOrder 2 .

oc:kn_63760415 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing any cold email" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Write like a peer, not a vendor. The email should read like it came from someone who understands their world. Use contractions. Count you/your sentences vs I/we sentences — reader perspective must dominate. If it sounds like marketing copy, rewrite it." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Buyers mentally categorize emails before reading — if it sounds like a sales pitch, it gets filtered regardless of content quality" .

oc:kn_693936a3 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing subject lines" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Subject lines must be 2–4 words, lowercase, no punctuation tricks. They should look like they came from a colleague, not a vendor. Examples: 'reply rates,' 'hiring ops,' 'Q2 forecast.' No product pitches, no urgency, no emojis, no prospect's first name in subject." ;
    oc:hasRationale "2-word subject lines get 60% more opens than 5-word. All-lowercase has highest open rates (Gong, 85M+ emails). Internal-looking subjects double open rates" .

oc:kn_75dc9430 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing the call-to-action" ;
    oc:directiveContent "One CTA per email. Use interest-based CTAs ('Worth exploring?' / 'Would this be useful?') over meeting requests. Higher in the org chart = less friction you can ask for." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Asking for a 30-minute call in the first email is like proposing on a first date. Low-friction CTAs make it easy to say yes with a one-line reply" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_90969f7b a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing follow-up emails" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use 'just checking in,' 'bumping this up,' 'did you see my last email,' or 'following up on my previous message' in follow-ups. Each follow-up must add genuinely new value — a different angle, fresh proof, or useful resource." ;
    oc:hasRationale "'I never heard back' causes a 12% drop in meeting booking rate (Gong). Zero-value follow-ups signal laziness and give the reader no reason to respond" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_a122b1da a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing any cold email" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never open with 'I hope this email finds you well,' 'My name is X and I work at Y,' or any AI-typical phrase like 'I came across your profile.' Avoid jargon: synergy, leverage, best-in-class, leading provider." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These phrases immediately signal mass automation or sales pitch, destroying trust before the reader sees your value" ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_a775bc78 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When setting expectations for cold email campaign performance" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Cold email reply rates have declined ~15% YoY from 7–8% (2020–2022) to 4–5.8% (2024–2025) due to inbox saturation and AI email flood. Writing craft matters more, not less — the gap between average and excellent is widening." ;
    oc:hasRationale "With 10+ cold emails per week hitting inboxes and Google's 0.1% complaint threshold, quality differentiation is the primary competitive advantage" .

oc:kn_b26ca0be a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When presenting cold email output to user" ;
    oc:directiveContent """## Email [N]: [Angle Description]
**Subject:** [2-4 words, lowercase]

[Body: 25-75 words, peer voice]

**CTA:** [Interest-based, one question]

---
**Quality Check:** [Pass/Fail on each criterion]""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Angle Description",
        "Body",
        "CTA",
        "N",
        "Quality Check",
        "Subject" .

oc:kn_c6a98eed a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before writing any cold email" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Check for .agents/product-marketing-context.md (or .claude/product-marketing-context.md) and read it before asking questions. Use that context and only ask for information not already covered." .

oc:req_6093c66e a oc:RequirementTool ;
    oc:isOptional true ;
    oc:requirementValue "file reader for .agents/product-marketing-context.md" .

